    mathSolution: "parallelStream() for concurrent processing",
    codeSolution:
      'import java.util.*;\nimport java.util.stream.*;\n\n// Sequential vs parallel performance\nList<Integer> numbers = IntStream.rangeClosed(1, 10_000_000)\n    .boxed()\n    .collect(Collectors.toList());\n\n// Sequential\nlong start = System.currentTimeMillis();\nlong sumSeq = numbers.stream()\n    .mapToLong(Integer::longValue)\n    .sum();\nlong end = System.currentTimeMillis();\nSystem.out.println("Sequential sum: " + sumSeq + ", time: " + (end - start) + "ms");\n\n// Parallel\nstart = System.currentTimeMillis();\nlong sumPar = numbers.parallelStream()\n    .mapToLong(Integer::longValue)\n    .sum();\nend = System.currentTimeMillis();\nSystem.out.println("Parallel sum: " + sumPar + ", time: " + (end - start) + "ms");\n\n// isParallel check\nStream<Integer> seqStream = numbers.stream();\nStream<Integer> parStream = numbers.parallelStream();\nSystem.out.println("Sequential is parallel? " + seqStream.isParallel());\nSystem.out.println("Parallel is parallel? " + parStream.isParallel());\n\n// Convert between sequential and parallel\nList<Integer> result = numbers.stream()\n    .parallel() // make parallel\n    .filter(n -> n % 1000 == 0)\n    .sequential() // back to sequential\n    .limit(5)\n    .collect(Collectors.toList());\nSystem.out.println("Result: " + result);\n\n// ForEach vs forEachOrdered\nSystem.out.println("\\nParallel forEach (unordered):");\nIntStream.range(1, 10)\n    .parallel()\n    .forEach(n -> System.out.print(n + " "));\n\nSystem.out.println("\\n\\nParallel forEachOrdered (preserves order):");\nIntStream.range(1, 10)\n    .parallel()\n    .forEachOrdered(n -> System.out.print(n + " "));\n\n// When not to use parallel - small datasets\nList<Integer> smallList = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);\nSystem.out.println("\\n\\nSmall list parallel overhead:");\nsmallList.parallelStream()\n    .forEach(n -> System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + ": " + n));',
